15:
Hey, you okay there? You've been 
sneezin' all da-a-atchoo!
21: Quiet, you two. My head is pounding...
23:
You two appear to be unwell. 
—Cough, cough.
28:
Even Stella's got a cold... That's pretty 
unusual.
39:
Let's see... Cough syrup, pain relievers, 
antiemetics for nausea, poultices... 
I'm all done on my end, Alk!
43:
I'm all done too! I've got egg drop 
soup and some pudding—
with a hearty dollop of honey! 
This should be easy on the stomach.
47: You, uh, sure made a LOT of medicine. If this stuff doesn't do the trick, I don't know what will.
51:
Better to have it and not need it. 
Thank you for letting me use your 
kitchen, by the way.
56:
Don't worry about it! If anything, we 
should be thanking you for going to 
all this trouble for us.
60: It's no trouble! This is my job, after all.
64:
It's weird that they all suddenly got 
sick at the same time. I wonder if they 
picked up a cold somewhere.
68:
The symptoms are similar, but the 
medicine they took earlier would've 
taken care of a cold by now.
69:
For now, all we can do is try to 
alleviate their symptoms while I work 
on a cure.
73:
Okay. Guess that means I'll have to 
keep making light, healthy meals to 
tide them over.
76:
What about you, Alk? How are you 
holding up?
80:
To be honest, I've been feeling a little 
light-headed my... self...
88:
(Populations develop different 
immunities, so international travelers 
risk catching and spreading otherwise 
benign diseases.)
92:
(Now if we consider that Alk and the 
others regularly travel to other 
WORLDS, then...)
107:
Thank you so much, Hartlief. 
Everyone's looking a lot better.
111:
For now, yes, but... As I explained to 
you earlier—
115:
Travel across worlds has medical 
risks, right?
116:
The example in the book was pretty 
scary, huh?
119:
Yes. Luckily, we managed to nip 
whatever you had in the bud, 
but it got me thinking.
120:
Naturally, the book doesn't account 
for travel across worlds, but it's a 
miracle you haven't experienced 
anything worse than a cold.
124:
I'm sorry... I don't mean to sound 
pessimistic. I hope I'm just jumping to 
conclusions.
129:
No, don't apologize! It's important 
research, and it definitely paid off—
everyone's right as rain thanks to you.
135:
You've been working non-stop, 
so it's about time you got some rest. 
I'll go whip up some dinner.
139:
(Stay positive, Hartlief. There's plenty I 
can do! For starters, I can write down 
a recipe for the medicine I made 
earlier.)
141:
(I should also build up my stock of 
generic medications like pain relievers 
and antidotes.)
145:
(Rather than mope about what COULD
 happen, I have to focus on making 
sure nothing DOES happen.)
147:
(And cross-world travel has lots of 
GOOD potential too! With the World 
Flipper and experienced companions, 
I might finally find it—)
148:
(Panaceum Kardifolia... The herb 
fabled to cure ANY ailment, and the 
"heart leaf" that inspired my name.)
154:
(If I put my mind to it, I can cure 
anything too! I just know it!)
